The smallest decision I would accept is: do not reuse the single-account handler in a loop. Add one bulk use-case entrypoint with a validated request model and an explicit per-item result enum, and keep the HTTP handler limited to parse/validate/map.

Why the shortcut is not acceptable:
- It validates too late. The requirement says reject before side effects if shape, count, or any ID is invalid.
- It uses exceptions as control flow across expected outcomes that are already typed.
- It cannot return the required per-account statuses plus derived summary counts.
- A two-account demo only proves the happy path, not the trust-boundary and mixed-outcome behavior.

Accepted implementation slice:
```ts
// Request boundary types
interface BulkActivateHttpBody {
  accounts: unknown;
}

type AccountId = string & { readonly __brand: 'AccountId' };

type ItemStatus =
  | 'activated'
  | 'already-active'
  | 'not-found'
  | 'unauthorized';

interface BulkActivateCommand {
  accountIds: AccountId[]; // validated: 1..100, distinct
}

interface ItemResult {
  accountId: AccountId;
  status: ItemStatus;
}

interface BulkActivateResult {
  items: ItemResult[];
  summary: Record<ItemStatus, number>;
}
```

```ts
function parseBulkActivate(body: unknown): BulkActivateCommand | ValidationError {
  if (!isObject(body) || !Array.isArray(body.accounts)) return invalid('accounts');
  if (body.accounts.length < 1 || body.accounts.length > 100) return invalid('accounts');

  const ids: AccountId[] = [];
  const seen = new Set<string>();

  for (const raw of body.accounts) {
    if (!isValidAccountId(raw)) return invalid('accounts');
    if (seen.has(raw)) return invalid('accounts');
    seen.add(raw);
    ids.push(raw);
  }

  return { accountIds: ids };
}

async function bulkActivate(cmd: BulkActivateCommand, actor: Actor): Promise<BulkActivateResult> {
  const items: ItemResult[] = [];

  for (const accountId of cmd.accountIds) {
    const allowed = await authz.canActivate(actor, accountId);
    if (!allowed) {
      items.push({ accountId, status: 'unauthorized' });
      continue;
    }

    const outcome = await accounts.activate(accountId);
    items.push({ accountId, status: outcome });

    if (outcome === 'activated') {
      await audit.recordActivation(actor, accountId);
    }
  }

  return {
    items,
    summary: deriveSummary(items),
  };
}
```

Notes on the slice:
- All request-shape, count, distinctness, and ID validation happens before any authorization, persistence, or audit call.
- Authorization is checked per account, as required.
- Expected business outcomes stay typed and explicit; no catch-all error swallowing.
- `summary` is derived from `items`, not maintained separately.

Focused tests I would require:
- Invalid body shape returns validation error and makes zero authz, persistence, or audit calls.
- More than 100 accounts returns validation error and makes zero side-effecting calls.
- Duplicate or malformed ID returns validation error and makes zero side-effecting calls.
- Mixed valid IDs produce exact per-item results: `activated`, `already-active`, `not-found`, `unauthorized`.
- Summary counts are derived from item results and match them exactly.
- Unauthorized accounts do not call activation or audit for that ID.
- Activated accounts record audit once; non-activated outcomes do not record activation audit.

That is the narrowest slice that satisfies the specification and resists the fully specified happy-path shortcut.
